		<table width="100%">
		<tr>
			<td>
				<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="3"><b>    Wizard Guide:Level 1-30</b></font>
					<br>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">
					<b><A href="mailto:xvoidlocke@aol.com">Hobono Bohobo [Finality,Tallon Zek Shard]</a> | 
		            7/6/2000 5:17:39 PM</b></font></p>
		         <a href="guides.asp">
		         <font face="verdana" size="2">Return to guide listing.</font></a>
					
					<p>
					<font face="verdana" size="2">Subj:	-Its from Nick.-<BR>
Date:	7/5/00 12:50:58 PM Central Daylight Time<BR>
From:	LordMystmoore<BR>
To:	jmarzluf@bellsouth.net<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Wizard Guide,levels 1-30<BR>
 <BR>
 [Guide:On]<BR>
 <BR>
 Basic Preperations.Locate your guild.Can't find it?Obtain a map from one of the many everquest websites.This map will show your guild location within your home city.<BR>
 Memorize your spells.Immediately.<BR>
 These spells are:<BR>
 [Frost Shock:Your first direct damage spell.]<BR>
 [Minor Shielding:The generic novice's shield.An unsophisticated form of magical shielding that will make it slightly more difficult for a monster to connect a powerful blow]<BR>
 <BR>
 Once you have finished,and have located your guild,take your Tome of Order and Discord...and promptly dismember it.Shred the leather bindings,and use the pages for kindling.I will tell you why.Enough NPCs hate you,and will try to kill you if you come within visual range...why allow the insignificant minority of idiot n00bs sporting they're stylish red-letter name to be able to kill you,and remove one of your hard-earned items?Stupid,eh?<BR>
 Now then.Take your Guild Letter,and hand it to your guild leader.You will gain experience,and be made an official member of your guild.If you somehow lost the letter,recreate your character.Otherwise,you will never...ever be able to train in your skills.<BR>
 <BR>
 No matter what race you choose,the MECHs believe firmly that the Qeynos region is the perfect place to gain experience,and grow in power.<BR>
 Obtain Spirit of Wolf from a shaman.They gain this spell the fastest,and it will increase your running speed,allowing you to easily outrun your foes.Your targets for levels 1-4 will be:<BR>
 a large rat-15hp<BR>
 a decaying skeleton-17hp<BR>
 a bat-14hp<BR>
 <BR>
 These creatures are slow,weak,and poorly armoured.They are not resiliant,so you will be able to easily finish them off.Place a single practice point into the skill:1h piercing.If you fail to do so,your dagger will never connect,and it will never rise in skill.Procede to annihilate all of the above creatures that con [white]...or,even fight.<BR>
 [Note:Never type /con...it is a hassle.The books,and several guides tell you this,because the author either was laughably ignorant,or too lazy to type an explanation.Unless you were a fool,and reassigned the  C button on your keyboard,it will serve the same purpose as pressing (return,then shift+?,and typing con.) Now that you've saved yourself some time,go back to hunting.]<BR>
 <BR>
 Levels 1-4 are not overly difficult.Simply slow.At level 1,you have a new target I neglected to mention.<BR>
 'a fire beetle'.You will find these con [yellow]...or gamble.This means it is 1-2 levels above you.Now,we come to the dangers of fighting these housecat-sized insects.They are social.What does this mean?<BR>
 <BR>
so*cial [1] (adjective)<BR>
 <BR>
 [Middle English, from Latin socialis, from socius companion, ally, associate; akin to Old English secg man, companion, Latin sequi to follow -- more at SUE]<BR>
 <BR>
 First appeared 14th Century<BR>
 <BR>
  1 : involving allies or confederates &lt;the Social War between the Athenians and their allies&gt;<BR>
  2 a : marked by or passed in pleasant companionship with one's friends or associates &lt;leads a very full ~ life&gt;<BR>
    b : SOCIABLE<BR>
    c : of, relating to, or designed for sociability &lt;a ~ club&gt;<BR>
  3 : of or relating to human society, the interaction of the individual and the group, or the welfare of human beings as members of society &lt;~ institutions&gt;<BR>
  4 a : tending to form cooperative and interdependent relationships with others of one's kind : GREGARIOUS<BR>
    b : living and breeding in more or less organized communities &lt;~ insects&gt;<BR>
    c of a plant : tending to grow in groups or masses so as to form a pure stand<BR>
  5 a : of, relating to, or based on rank or status in a particular society &lt;a member of our ~ set&gt;<BR>
    b : of, relating to, or characteristic of the upper classes<BR>
    c : FORMAL<BR>
 <BR>
...No...these are not friendly beetles.Do not attempt to speak to them.NPCs are not sentient beings.They respond on que,and only certain humanoid named NPCs do so.If they respond,chances are they are related to quests.However,quests will be discussed in other guides,not this one.<BR>
Social creatures come to the aid of their fellows.In other words,if you are fighting a single fire beetle,and another 4 decide to walk by,they will decide that it is highly 'unsociable' to annihilate one of their species,and they will inevitably assault you,quickly rending you and killing you before you understand what occured.Spirit of Wolf is what will allow you to kill these.You'll notice that your mana reserves,which will be 20-30,depending on your intelligence,at level one seems to recharge rapidly,even while standing and fighting.Your going to be introduced to the wonders of Kiting.As you know,an angry monster will chase you until dead,or until you cross a zoneline,or die by its hands(or pincers,species pending)...However,you can take this predictability,and turn it against them as a powerful weapon.Find a fire beetle,and with Spirit of Wolf(and run) in effect,cast 'Shock of Frost' ...the creature will start after you.If possible,toss one more...two hits,and it has not struck you once.At this point,turn,and run for the gate to North Qeynos,but do not get near the guards.Your not fleeing.Your kiting.Once you've decided the beetle is a fair distance away,stop running,and as soon as you release the forward arrow key,press the right arrow key,causing you to COMPLETELY stop all forward motion by pivoting sharply.As soon as you pivot,rapidly click on Shock of Frost until it is cast once more...Repeat until the creature supposedly more powerful than you has died.If you run out of mana reserves,run about in circles,leading the monster around as it follows you but never touches you,like a 'Kite' (Thus the term)...until you see your mana reserve grow a wee bit.This growth spurt occurs about every 6 seconds.Once you have enough power for another blast,do so.Notice the experience gain off of a single 'gamble' kill.<BR>
 <BR>
Your targets at level 1-4:<BR>
a large rat<BR>
a bat<BR>
a decaying skeleton<BR>
a fire beetle(Use Kiting methods described in detail above.Beware of attracting more beetles through socializing)<BR>
a snake<BR>
all Kliknik varieties,save the Queen<BR>
Veer away from:<BR>
Queen Kliknik:(Roughly 11 times your level)<BR>
A skeleton:(It is hostile,and will attack you if you come to close...roughly 8 times your level)<BR>
a zombie:(Hostile as well,it packs a very nasty punch,and will kill you in a heartbeat.Fortunately,it is relatively rare.)<BR>
all Dark Paws:(Note:These Dark Paw gnolls will make fools of themselves by shouting their threats,and proceding to commit suicide by running straight down the dirt path,into the Gates of qeynos,to be slaughtered by the city guard in one,to two hits.)<BR>
 <BR>
Once you have gained level 4,you should notice you have accumulated much money from the treasure you have gleaned from selling the various appendages retrieved from the bodies of your foes.Note that decaying skeletons occasionally carry rusty weapons,which can be sold for a few pieces of gold,and also note that 'a gnoll pup' is hostile but weak...more importantly,they drop Containers...'a backpack' adds 8 more slots of inventory space.Murdering the pups for their small amounts of coin,and the occasional container is also a good idea...it also makes the residents of the city,and some other surrounding areas like you.If they like you,they sell things cheaper,and buy things for more money.Some quests also require a certain 'likeability' to be performed by someone.<BR>
Taking your money,head to your guild and purchase the following spells:<BR>
Root:(Cast this on yourself over and over until your skill is maxed out.Always keep Alteration at its maximum.Your skill maxes out at 5x your level+5(So,at level 4...5x4=20+5=25...25 would be the maximum skill level in all your magical skills.A higher Alteration skill means a longer,stronger root.)Root immobilizes your opponent,allowing you to blast it away,until the root breaks.Also note that if Root is resisted,the monster will become agitated,and it will immediately go for your throat.<BR>
Icestrike:A rain spell.Used in conjunction with Root,it will strike said monster(in outdoor areas) 3 times,for -10 a hit.Each strike will give the creature a chance to break the Root spell.<BR>
Shock of Fire:A more powerful direct-damage,non-lineofsight spell.Its easier to Kite creatures with this...It strikes for 11 points of Fire Damage...and eventualy increases to a maximum of 16 points of fire damage...however,by the time it maxes out,it becomes utterly useless,and is insignificant damage to the creatures you'll be facing.<BR>
Gate:Teleport yourself back home.<BR>
Congratulations.At level 4,you've graduated to the Qeynos Hills zone.<BR>
<BR>
Your targets at levels 4-8:<BR>
a grey wolf [Level 3-5,social]<BR>
a rabid wolf[Level 3-5,social with wolves/rabid wolves]<BR>
a large bat[Level 2-3]<BR>
a large snake[Level 4-5]<BR>
a brown bear[Level 4-5]-Hits hard for its Level,but has Low hp-<BR>
a gnoll scout[Level 4-6]<BR>
a gnoll[Levels 4-6...drops cloth armor,good coins,rusty weapons,and Gnoll Fangs.Give the fangs collected to Captain Tillin...either a stack of 4,or one at a time,for amazingly good exp.]<BR>
a gnoll pup[Level 1]<BR>
a skeleton[Level 5-7]<BR>
a gnoll watcher[These spawn in groups of three near the entrance to Blackburrow.Make sure you can handle all 3 before attacking,as they will socialize eachother.]<BR>
a decaying skeleton[Level 1]<BR>
a large rat[Level 1]<BR>
a giant rat[Level 6-8]<BR>
a giant bat[Level 6-8]<BR>
a gnoll hunter[Rare spawn.<BR>
Veer away from:<BR>
Holly Windstalker/Cros Treewind: [While fighting a bear/wolf ...They are both level 25+,and they'll slaughter those who 'injure they're animal friends' ...feh...druids and rangers...Lie down with the wolves,wake up with rabies...]<BR>
a dread corpse:[Level 10-11.These spawn near the ruins close to the entrance of Surefall Glade.They also result in a quick death,if your not in a relatively large group of level 8-9's.They have an effect called 'Dread Touch',which lowers your strength by 10.Oh no.Strength is -oh so important- to a wizard. -_-;; ]<BR>
a putrid skeleton:[Level 7-9.They look like normal skeletons,but hit harder,and breath on you occasionally.The effect 'Putrid Breath' is a disease-based spell that negates your health regeneration.Cure it with Cure Disease.]<BR>
<BR>
Once you have attained the 7th level,you may want to group for the first level of Blackburrow.If someone shouts train,find a place that is far away from the entrance/exit of the dungeon.Bringing us to the Wizards nemesis.More so than others,we fear the word 'Train'.The reason for this,is we do not have the AC or HP of a Barbarian warrior,to withstand the barrage of attacks from monsters in the passing train and get into the zoneline in time,nor do we have the skeletal fiend or elemental goon to run interference while we make a hastey retreat.We have our skill,cunning,and legs for running.<BR>
<BR>
Train: A long string of monsters varying widely in level and toughness,following a single monster initially angered by a player,as he runs for safety.<BR>
<BR>
A train occurs when said idiot marches into the depths of the dungeon unprepared,and attacks the first thing he sees,forgetting that its cousin,next-door neighbor,and distant relative sitting nearby would find that very naughty of him.He gets more than he bargained for...4-7 monsters,instead of the initial 1.So,he does the logical thing.Retreat.As he does so,he runs by other monsters...and the 7 monsters chasing him tell the nearby monsters how mean and bad said idiot was,so now there are around 10-15 different creatures,from different parts of the dungeon,all wanting the poor suckers blood.He makes it across the zoneline,with the monsters close behind...and so,the 15 cheated monsters decide to make the trek to the zoneline worthwhile,and break off on different people...how nasty would it be to walk in at level 7,and be attacked by 3 level 13s?Very nasty.When you hear the word 'Train'...seek cover until the train subsides.Pathing causes the monsters to go back where they came from,after they haven't had anything to kill for awhile.<BR>
After gaining level 8,you finally get a spell that does decent damage.Two,to be exact.So,we will discuss 'cheap damage' tactics.First,march over to your guild,and buy the following spells:<BR>
<BR>
Shock of Ice:32-38 pts of Ice-Based damage,for 30 mana.A good,relatively efficient spell.<BR>
Fire Bolt:45-51 damage,slowcasting Fire-based Bolt spell.Bolts are wonderful for 'cheap damage' tactics.<BR>
A bolt has significantly longer range than a shock spell,but suffers from Line of Sight issues...if the creature is behind a tree,the bolt will touch the tree and dissapate,doing nothing and wasting your mana.<BR>
Lesser Shielding:An upgrade to your shielding line of spells.How nice.More HP,and AC.Your still not going to be tanking,so you might take 2 more hits to get killed.Still,it adds magic resistance,which is nice.<BR>
<BR>
...If you have the money to burn,buy the best armor you can find...ussually cloth,or preferrably raw silk...and some intelligence jewelry.<BR>
Once you've attained level 8,you've graduated to West Karana.<BR>
<BR>
Your targets at levels 8-12<BR>
a giant spider[Level 7-9.Inflicts Poison.Fight in groups]<BR>
a giant beetle[Level 7-9.Slow,and easily Kiteable,even without SoW.So KITE!]<BR>
a grizzly bear[Level 8-10.Hits hard,but has low HP for its level.]<BR>
<BR>
Veer away from:<BR>
Hill Giants:[They're big.They're bad.They hate you.If you see one,scream like a woman,and run.]<BR>
ANYTHING that cons red is probably going to be hostile,aside from NPC humanoids.Stay away from them!<BR>
<BR>
Keep your alteration maxed out...your going to be using root alot after level 16.<BR>
<BR>
Once you have reached level 12...smile.You've just become powerful for your level.Welcome to the world of Norrath.Let's talk about the spell Shock of Lightning.<BR>
<BR>
This spell is wonderful.When a young wizard obtains it,his/her face lights up.While expensive at level 12,it quickly becomes an affordable way to ruin a monster's day.Let's look at the statistics on the spell you'll be using into your late twenties.<BR>
<BR>
Shock of Lightning<BR>
Casting Time:2.2 seconds<BR>
Mana cost:60<BR>
Range:200 feet<BR>
Damage:78-83<BR>
Resistances invoked:Magical<BR>
Added effects:1 second interrupt stun,1/2 foot knockback.Wonderful against NPC casters.It slaps them hard,and interrupts their spell.<BR>
<BR>
Congratulations,you've just graduated...<BR>
If this is your first character,and you've used my guide to get you this far...I am impressed.Not many first-timers pick the Wizard for their character choice.However,I am also proud.You have persevered.Leveling a new Wizard is like climbing a ladder,with half of the rungs missing...but,you have performed well...and now,you have been rewarded.Behold,the spells of the senior apprentice to Wizardry:<BR>
<BR>
Shock of Lightning:Your first respectable DD.78-83 points of magical damage...plus a pretty explosion of red sparks.<BR>
Halo of Light:Cloth cap on your head?Summon a Halo of Light...its better than a Greater Lightstone,and affords the wearer 3 AC.Not bad for a human,or erudite wizard cursed with a lack of racial nightvision.<BR>
Bind Affinity:A wonderful spell.You can now cater to the n00bs who came all the way from Freeport,and wanna make Qeynos they're new home.Simply group with the person,target them,and cast Bind Affinity.Or,target yourself,choose where you wish to appear when you cast Gate,and cast the spell.It sets their 'home point' to whereever they were standing when the spell took effect.<BR>
<BR>
Aggro,and You<BR>
Now then...a word about aggro.Normally,in your younger years,you could repeatedly blast MOBs with Shock of Ice.Your tanks,if you had any,would be doing enough damage to keep up with the measley -40 of your DD.Now...you are a bit more noticeable.If you hit the creature too hard,too fast with your spell,it'll decide your more irritating,and it will attempt to kill you.Let the tank hurt the creature a tiny bit before blasting it.Find a group for the Elite Ledge in Blackburrow.That is your target for levels 12-16.Without a group,kill rabid beasts...ESPECIALLY Rabid Grizzly bears...and take their pelts to Priestess Caulria...she resides within the 'Flying Saucer' in Qeynos' Temple of Life.This quest gives incredible amounts of experience,and by the time you do this enough to level into 16...well,you'll be very well-liked in the Temple of Life.<BR>
<BR>
Avoid aggro by...waiting until the tank has pounded the creature severely...until it has about 80% of its health left.Then,blast it.Watch its health plummet at a ridiculously fast rate.As it turns to run,knock it dead with Shock of Lightning.<BR>
<BR>
A wizard becomes dangerous at level 16...<BR>
<BR>
You've done it.It probably took a week or so,but you've reached level 16...Now,it has gone slower than most Wizards,because you could have leveled faster,easier by killing the creatures within the Northern Plains of Karana.<BR>
I'll tell you why you didn't.<BR>
#1:Having done the rabid animal quest with Bear pelts,you've probably accumulated over 40 platinum pieces.<BR>
#2:Having slaughtered elite gnoll guards in Blackburrow since level 12,you also made considerable money off of the spiked/studded leather collars you collected.<BR>
<BR>
While you could have leveled faster in NK (North Karana),when you gained level 16,you'd find that the fire beetle eyes you collected off the giant beetle varieties had gained you very,very little money,leaving you to use your level 12 DD until you had enough money to buy the first triple-digit damage DD.<BR>
Buy these spells before you go and become a real adventurer.I am sure it's been boring hanging around the neighborhood of Qeynos,and most people long for travel at about this point in their career.Luckily,you get several spells that make traveling very,very easy.<BR>
<BR>
Purchase these spells from the appropriate vendors:<BR>
<BR>
Flame Shock:102-110 points of fire damage.This is going to be your main DD.Its more mana efficient than Shock of Lightning,although slightly slower to cast,and rather costly mana-wise.You can buy it at the Qeynos Wizard's Guild.<BR>
Lightning Bolt:A powerful bolt attack...the last one you'll ever get.It deals -117,to -125...Line of Sight,best to pull with it.<BR>
Heat Sight:Finally...get rid of your Halo of Light,and look around for a Runed Circlet.With this spell,you will be able to see very,very well at night.It adds Infravision temporarily.Buy it in the Erudin Library.<BR>
Invisiblity:Ohhhh,my.Unless you were smarter than I was,this is hell to cast.It fizzles...and fizzles...and fizzles...and fizzles...and fizzles...and fizzles.I've managed to deplete my entire mana bar before getting a single,successful casting.MAX your divination skill.After that skill reaches about 40,you'll stop fizzling as often.It has a random duration,so be sure to con everything you think could rip you to tiny pieces.Buy it in the Qeynos Wizard Guild,or Erudin,depending on yer faction.<BR>
Shielding:Much better...+50 HP,and +10 AC,and it adds a bit of Magic Resistance.You can benefit from this.<BR>
Shieldskin:It requires a Cat's Eye Agate to cast...2gp per...it adds a skin that absorbs about 70 points of damage,before falling.Buy this,and Shielding in Qeynos,or Erudin Library...as for the gemns...they can be bought in the Jewel section of Firepride's in North Qeynos.Near Nerissa Clothspinner.<BR>
<BR>
Research...Is it really worth it?<BR>
Frankly,I've yet to find a point in time where it was.Monsters above level 15 are going to be dropping (rarely) 'scraps of paper...and chunks of rock' ...The rocks are Runes.They can be combined within a Lexicon (Our researching device) in the correct order,to occasionally create a research-only spell.However,the Runes dropped are rarely the ones you've been 'looking' for.And,more often than not,the failed research attempt destroys the Runes.I suggest buying your Research spells,and start practicing Research at level 30.You'll want it obscenely high if you wish to research Ice Comet.Sell the runes that you find,or stockpile them.You may need extra cash,and runes sell for about 5 gp-2pp,depending on their rarity.<BR>
<BR>
Your next hunting zone is North Karana.Enter West Karana by following the path in Qeynos Hills,and taking a right when you come to the road marker.Its hard to miss...it says <BR>
WEST KARANA---------&gt;<BR>
Once you enter Western Karana,follow the path until you leave the Canyon...walk 3ft past the Brother Chintle...if its Brother Trintle...Slaughter the fool.He is a traitor.And a weakling.He likes to cast 'Strike',a -7 DD.As menacing as he sounds...he really is a pushover.Now then...once you've passed the tree the Brother stands near,take a right...and walk forward,hopefully having Invisibility and Heatsight in effect.<BR>
With the zonewall on your right,and open spaces on your left,you should eventually come to a village of Barbarians.Once there,follow the shoreline closely...and follow it left.Its a long walk...and stay out of the fields near the farms.Level 18 Undead NPCs live there.Scarecrows.They'll be good targets at level 20,but stay away for now.They see through Invis.<BR>
<BR>
Targets at level 16-20<BR>
a pincer beetle:Level 12-14 (These will ussually be blue,and they are slower than your natural running speed.You can Kite them without SoW,but its better to do it with SoW,in case you run into something nastier.)<BR>
a borer beetle:Level 15-17 (Again,slower than SoW.)<BR>
a scythe beetle:Level 17-19 (You can sometimes kill these at level 16...resists will be bad,but you may succeed in killing a gamble/tombstone.Kiting of course.As always,they are slower than your Running speed.)<BR>
a griffawn:Level 14-17 (These are very nasty.A level 20 cannot stay in melee range for long with this one.It packs consistent double-attacks,for -30 a piece.Use SoW,as they are pretty fast...the best tactic is to pull with a Lightning Bolt,and root it before it gets to you.Then,knock it down with Flame Shocks,or Kite it.<BR>
a highland lion:Level 16-18 (Be careful.They hit hard,they double-attack for -30...and they can outrun you,even if you are SoWed.If yer aggroed by one,best to know where you are if you die,and run for the guard tower,or stone bridge.)<BR>
<BR>
Veer away from...<BR>
a hill giant:Self-explanatory.<BR>
a griffon:They see right through invisibility.<BR>
a griffenne:They see invis. as well,but aren't able to outrun SoW,like the Griffon.<BR>
GrimFeather:OOooh...faster than a griffon,nastier too.A rarespawn 'King Griffon' ...He likes to sneak up on you while your meditating,and double-attack you for -95.<BR>
Zahal the Vile:A wandering level 28 Ghoul.He is a rarespawn as well.<BR>
A mistwolf:They are green.They are fast.They are annoying,because they are just powerful enough to aggro you,even though they are far weaker than you,several of them slowly grinding you down with occasional double -24's can add up,as they are social.Best to run to the guards,instead of waste mana.<BR>
<BR>
Make sure to bind yourself at the Wizard's Spires...those huge towers near the Stone Bridge.Those are the devices you'll be using,at level 20.You can hop to 3 of the 4 continents instantly.Thats why the melee classes get jealous of us.<BR>
<BR>
Congratulations.You've just attained level 20...<BR>
Don't be a fool.Your level 20,so your probably riding the rush of having your last name,which seperates you from the newbies.You are wrong.Level 20 is hell to get through.Your getting a new DD at this level,however,its a useless one.Your going to be using the same DD you've been using since level 16.<BR>
You are not 'elite'.<BR>
You are not super-powerful,now that you've gained a surname.<BR>
You are in no way 'special'.<BR>
<BR>
Welcome to Hell.<BR>
One comforting thing is...you can now make money far more easily than before...and that is because you now have access to your personal teleportations.<BR>
<BR>
Spells to buy...<BR>
<BR>
North Gate:Transports you to the Stone Bridge in North Karana...conveniently,this also brings you straight to an NPC you can camp for experience,and very little faction loss,all the way up to level 30.In addition to this wonderful NPC,which never double-attacks,and has no ranged attack...You are also taken to the doorstep of Bilbis Briar,a merchant you can buy food from,and sell loot to.Meaning you can be a trade caravan of sorts,picking up items from far-off lands,and sending them back to Antonica to sell for exorbitant prices.<BR>
Fay Gate:This transports you into Greater Faydark.Grab a map,and make your way into Lesser Faydark...then,hug the right zonewall,preferrably with Invis,and SoW on.Its a long trip,but you'll eventually come to a ring of ruins near a mountain pass.Bind yourself at the entrance to the mountain pass...this is where you'll be hunting...from level 20...to level 40+,if need be.Welcome to Mistmoore,home of good loot,low resists,and great experience.You'll have to have a group,however.Cast invisibility upon yourself,as about 99.9% of the MOBs here...even the high level ones...cannot see through it.Take your first left,and follow the ramp down...take another left,and make your way onto the top of the rise...this is called the 'Hill'.Its ussually camped constantly,and you can probably get into it.They like Wizards,as we can demolish the caster Pledge Familiars once we attain level 20 and above.<BR>
Toxx Gate:You can now transport onto the continent of Odus.Cast True North,and head North til you see a bridge.Cross the bridge,and follow the right riverbank...you'll eventually come to the zonewall,and a small group of huts.Follow the zonewall right,and you'll find the cliffside entrance to Erudin,home of all your more exotic spells...like teleportations.<BR>
Force Shock:Possibly the biggest dissappointment a wizard will ever have.It either strikes your opponent for -171...or,it is completely resisted,and wastes 120 points of mana.In other words,its an -all-or-nothing- ...Have an enchanter in your group debuff the monsters Magic Resistance first.Then,after it is severely injured,blast it once with this to 'frighten' it.No enchanter?Stick to Flame Shock.<BR>
Elemental Shield:A must-have.Although most of the creatures you'll be fighting don't cast spells,at higher levels they will...this spell adds an additional +15 Cold and Fire resistance.Very,very helpful.If you bought Resistant Skin,you'll be able to add to all of your resistances.<BR>
Tishan's Clash:Without a doubt,one of the perma-mem's...Your going to be using this spell until the high 40's.It causes about -30 in Magical Damage,and stuns the creature for 5 seconds,allowing you to either run,or root it for more nuking.Very useful against spellcasters,as it interrupts their casting.<BR>
Enstill:An upgraded root.It costs about 2x as much,and casts a bit slower,but if it holds,it keeps the MOB stuck for alot longer.<BR>
<BR>
Your targets at level 20:<BR>
a scythe beetle: [All of these will be blue by now.You can easily torch them,though I don't suggest using Force Shock on them,unless you have got tons of mana.]<BR>
a griffawn: [Kite these with SoW...but only a rare few will be blue.Most will be green.Don't underestimate them.They can kick your arse all across Norrath...you still have the AC of a level 9 tank.]<BR>
Cordelia Minster:<BR>
Faction Loss:<BR>
AntonicanBards(She lowers all the factions your going to be worried about by insignificant incriments.You can make back all the faction you lose with her by killing about 2 'a gnoll' 's in Blackburrow.<BR>
GuardsofQeynos:(Again,very,very little faction.I've trashed her for 7 levels nonstop,and Guards still conned Warmly to me.)<BR>
KnightsofTruth:(The oh-so-useless Paladin guild in Freeport.Personally,I can't find a reason to visit that pitiful excuse for a city.Qeynos is much closer,and easier to get around in.)<BR>
MayongMistmoore:(This faction goes up.the head vampyre,level 53,in Mistmoore will eventually like you.)<BR>
RingofScale:(Worshippers of Dragons..including Bandits and Raiders...and Putrid Skeletons in South Karana...will like you.)<BR>
Cordelia Minster is level 19-22.Easily pulverized by kiting her around with Flame Shock.Don't bother rooting,just use Twistkiting,a tactic you learned at level 1.Keep her away from the guards by pulling her away,towards the West Karana zone.Guards will help her out if they see you killing her.<BR>
<BR>
Targets will no longer be listed...you'll be given target zones...and after 30,its up to you...<BR>
Your zone(grouped) is:Castle Mistmoore...Hill Group,or Cove Group.Preferrably Hill.Its got a straight retreat path to the zone.<BR>
Your zone(solo) is:North Karana.See above targets...when the MOBs start conning green,start killing Cordelia Minster.She'll give you experience up until level 30.<BR>
<BR>
These zones will allow you to gain levels 20-30.<BR>
<BR>
Your spells:Level 24<BR>
Frost Shock:An upgraded DD.More efficient,faster reloading,less resisted Cold-based DD.It deals -169 at level 24,and peaks at level 30,doing -187.<BR>
Cazic,Common,Nek,Ro,and West Gates:Useful additions to your teleportation destinations.Nektulos is risky,as wandering dark-elven guards can sometimes kill you...Cazic Gate is useless,teleporting you into the center of a high level dungeon.Its a deathtrap,so do not use it.The others are safe,unless a wandering Hill Giant decides to sit down and take a nap on the teleport pad.<BR>
Leatherskin:Requires a Bloodstone...A +120 HP Skin.When this is in effect,you can briefly tank,allowing the MOB to attack the invuln-skin while the injured tank gets healed by a priestclass.<BR>
Major Shielding:+75 HP,and +25 AC,along with a +15 Magic Resistance buff.Very,very nice,as it stacks with all the clerical/druidic buffs.<BR>
Levitate:Buy it in Halas...this allows you to float,enabling you to fall great distances and incur no damage.It also lets you run right across Dagnor's Cauldron without recieving any damage those Melee classes suffer,when they fall off the jagged rocks.It requires 1 Batwing,gotten off of Bats.Not Giant Bats,or Large bats...just 'Bats'.It -can- be cast on others.<BR>
<BR>
Spells:Level 29<BR>
Inferno Shock:A mighty blast of flame,dealing over -230 points of damage.<BR>
Thunderstrike:An upgraded,less resisted Force Shock-like spell...same reload time,but it has a massive knockback,and pulverizes those casters if it doesn't get resisted.Use sparingly without an enchanter.<BR>
Bonds of Force:An area-effect snarespell.Pull with it...if it doesn't stick,don't use it again.MOBs will get in range of the spell,and you'll be too close to the MOB when the spell fires,thus catching you in its radius.<BR>
You'll be snared.<BR>
North,Fay,and Toxx portals:You can now transport others to these locations...as well as charge them much shiny coinage.In a word...'suuu-weeeeet.'Simply group with them,and cast the spell.<BR>
Evacuate:North:A faster-casting evacuate spell...it transports your group to North Karana,but casts about 7 seconds faster.Used when your group is too far from the zoneline,and they're getting pounded by a train.<BR>
<BR>
-End Guide-
			<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</font></p>
					</p>
